Two likely causes:

**1. `BindingContext` is never set.** You need to assign your ViewModel to the page:

```csharp
// In code-behind (e.g., MainPage.xaml.cs)
public MainPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = new MyViewModel();
}
```

**2. ViewModel doesn't notify the UI of changes.** Your properties must raise `PropertyChanged`:

```csharp
public class MyViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
{
    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler PropertyChanged;

    private string _title;
    public string Title
    {
        get => _title;
        set { _title = value; PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new PropertyChangedEventArgs(nameof(Title))); }
    }
}
```

Or, simpler — inherit from `ObservableObject` (MVVM Community Toolkit) and use `[ObservableProperty]`:

```csharp
public partial class MyViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _title;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _description;
}
```

The most common culprit is the missing `BindingContext`.
